{"title_page": "Fritz Brase", "text_new": "{{short description|German military bandmaster, conductor, and composer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Fritz Brase\n| image         = Colonel Fritz Brase.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Signed portrait of<br>Brase in Irish Army uniform\n| birth_name    = Friedrich Wilhelm Anton Brase\n| birth_date    = 4 May 1875\n| birth_place \u00a0 = [[Egestorf (Deister)|Egestorf]], Germany\n| death_date    = 1 December 1940 (age 65)\n| death_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Army band leader\n| years_active  = 1893\u20131940\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Friedrich Wilhelm Anton Brase''' (4 May 1875 \u2013 1 December 1940) was a German military [[bandmaster]], [[Conducting|conductor]], and [[composer]] who was mainly active in Dublin, Ireland, as leader of the first [[Irish Defence Forces School of Music|Army School of Music]] in the [[Irish Free State]].\n\n==Life==\nBrase was the son of a miller born in [[Egestorf (Deister)|Egestorf]] near Hanover, Germany. Brase studied at the [[University of Music and Theatre Leipzig|Conservatory of Music at Leipzig]] where his teachers included [[Carl Reinecke]], [[Hans Sitt]], and [[Salomon Jadassohn]]. In 1923 he emigrated to Ireland,<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/> and a few years later he and his wife Elsa had a daughter, Mona, who was born while they lived at the [[Curragh Camp]].<ref name=\"RT\u00c9 doc\">{{cite AV media |people=Ryan, Captain Joseph (writer & presenter); Hughes, John (producer) |title=Wilhelm Maestro |medium=[https://podcast.rasset.ie/podcasts/2013/pc/pod-v-19038957m04swilhelmmaestrodoconone-pid0-3424608_audio.mp3 ''Documentary on One'' Podcast] |publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] |location=Dublin |date=1989 |url=https://www.rte.ie/radio1/doconone/2013/0612/647443-podcast-wilhelm-maestro-irish-army-school-of-music-band-no-1/ }}</ref> The family moved to accommodation in [[Beggars Bush Barracks]] and later bought their own house in the Dublin suburb of [[Sandymount]].<ref name=\"RT\u00c9 doc\"/>\n\nIn 1940, Brase died the day after he retired and was interred in [[Mount Jerome Cemetery and Crematorium|Mount Jerome Cemetery]], Dublin, when the No. 1 Irish Army Band played.<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\">{{Cite web |url=http://stores.militaryhistoryshop.com/blog/fritz-brase-irelands-prussian-bandmaster-/ |title=Fritz Brase: Ireland's Prussian Bandmaster |date=2016-01-20 |publisher=Brandenburg Historica |access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> His daughter Mona, who died on 2 November 2014, is also buried in Mount Jerome Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |title=BRASE, Mona: Death notice |work=Family Notices |publisher=[[Irish Times]] |date=5 November 2014 |url=https://notices.irishtimes.com/death/brase-mona/39512965 |accessdate=15 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\nA street in [[M\u00fcnster]] is named Braseweg in his memory.<ref>{{OpenStreetMap maps |url=https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=braseweg#map=18/51.97990/7.64548 |title=Braseweg, M\u00fcnster |accessdate=14 March 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"RT\u00c9 doc\"/>\n\n==Musical career==\nIn 1893, he enlisted in the military band at [[B\u00fcckeburg]] where his abilities as conductor and arranger qualified him for further studies at the [[Berlin University of the Arts|Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik, Berlin]], studying with [[Joseph Joachim]] and [[Max Bruch]].\nIn 1906, he was appointed conductor of the Infantry Regiment 13's band at M\u00fcnster and received early encouragement, when in 1909, at the age of 34, he was promoted [[Prussia|Prussian]] \"K\u00f6niglicher Musikdirektor\" (Royal Music Director).<ref>Joseph Ryan, \"Brase, [Wilhelm] Fritz [Anton]\", in ''The Enyclopaedia of Music in Ireland'' (Dublin: UCD Press, 2013), p. 124.</ref> In 1911, he was appointed conductor of the [[1st (Emperor Alexander) Guards Grenadiers]], \"one of the most prestigious positions in the world of German military music\".<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/> Following the German defeat in World War I, Brase was discharged from service in April 1919 and spent the following four years in various consignments including conducting a police band in Berlin.\n\nWhen Brase emigrated to Ireland in March 1923, he was attracted by the option of a rank as full colonel and  to take up the position of the first leader of the Army School of Music in the newly established Irish Free State.<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/> Until 1928, he created four military bands in cooperation with a compatriot, Captain Friedrich Christian Sauerzweig, with Brase focusing on the \"Army No. 1 Band\". For independent Ireland, bringing over musicians from Germany was one way of breaking free from British influence.<ref>Joan FitzPatrick Dean, [https://books.google.de/books?id=8-jqBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA148&dq=Irish+Defence+Forces+School+of+Music&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Irish%20Defence%20Forces%20School%20of%20Music&f=false ''All Dressed Up. Modern Irish Historical Pageantry''] (Syracuse, NY: Syracuse University Press, 2014), pp. 147\u2013148.</ref> With his band, Brase toured Ireland extensively between the mid-1920s and early 1930s, playing at many festive occasions, both indoors and in public spaces. He also initialised a regular series of band concerts for primary schools in Dublin which, over the years, were attended by thousands of Irish school children.<ref>Ryan (2013).</ref> In 1927, he also co-founded the Dublin Philharmonic Society, a successful orchestra and chorus with a brass section recruited from the army band, which he directed until 1936 when he had to resign for health reasons. At the Army School of Music, he educated a number of prominent Irish musicians including [[Michael Bowles]], [[Arthur Duff]], and Dermot O'Hara.\n\n{{Quote box|width=300px|bgcolor=#E0E6F8|align=right|quote='''Recognition of Brase's contribution and achievements: [[Sir Anthony Esmonde, 15th Baronet|Anthony Charles Esmonde]] in [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] in November 1952'''<br>\n\n''When musical broadcasts were first organised in this country, under the late Colonel Fritz Brase, a German, he did not import a whole lot of foreign musicians. He recognised the fact that there was a fund of musical talent latent in the Irish people and he set out to develop that talent... but I think it is a pity that his policy was not continued, that this talent was not sought out and developed on a more extensive scale. That appears to me to be the difficulty with the orchestras in this country\u2014 that the talent that is there has not been sought out by the officials, the directors or whoever is in control of [[Radio \u00c9ireann]] and utilised so as to give employment to the fullest extent to Irish musicians and artistes.''<ref>{{cite web |title=D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann debate - Thursday, 6 Nov 1952 |work=D\u00e1il debates |publisher=[[Houses of the Oireachtas]] |date=6 November 1952 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1952-11-06/40/?highlight%5B0%5D=brase |accessdate=23 March 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/>}}\n\nBrase's influence on the cultural life of the nascent Irish republic was considerable and he was an ambitious composer who also wrote many works outside the military band repertory. He wrote a Symphony in D major that was performed in M\u00fcnster in 1908 and a number of other orchestral scores. For the army bands, he wrote many original scores (including the ''General Mulcahy March'' and six ''Irish Fantasias'') and arranged numerous Irish traditional tunes for military band. His first ''Irish Fantasia'' was played in 1926 at the opening broadcast of 2RN, the predecessor of today's [[Radio Telef\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]. He also wrote the station's official arrangement of the Irish national anthem.<ref>Ryan (2013).</ref>\n\n==German colony in Ireland==\nBrase was one of a small number of Germans and Austrians living in Ireland in the 1930s, several of whom had been brought there by the Irish Government, that included Brase and others, mostly involved in new industry the fledgling state was trying to develop. Otto Bene, leader of the [[Nazi Party]] in Britain and Ireland, living in London, visited Dublin to celebrate Hitler's birthday on 20 April 1933 in the presence of Brase and several others of the German colony that took place in the German Legation. Bene was responsible for recruiting Germans to the Nazi Party.<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\"/>{{rp|57, photo inter 128\u2013129}}\n\nEncouraged by Bene, the German colony set up a branch of the Nazi Party in 1934. Brase was its first elected chairman, however, when he requested permission from the [[Irish Army]] to lead the group, it was clearly suggested he choose between the two. He chose the army and his career<ref>David O'Donoghue, [https://www.historyireland.com/20th-century-contemporary-history/state-within-a-state-the-nazis-in-neutral-ireland/ \"State within a state: the Nazis in neutral Ireland\"], in ''History Ireland'', vol. 14 no. 6 (November/December 2006).</ref> allowing [[Adolf Mahr]], another German immigree and director of the [[National Museum of Ireland]], to assume the position.<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\">{{cite book |last=Mullins |first=Gerry |title=Dublin Nazi No. 1: The Life of Adolf Mahr |publisher=[[Liberties Press]] |date=2007 |location=Dublin |pages= |isbn=978-1-905483-20-4 }}</ref>{{rp|56\u201357}} Bene again came to Dublin in 1935 to attend Brase' 60th birthday party in the family home in [[Sandymount]].<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\nThe soccer match between Germany and Ireland, that Ireland won 5 to 2, at [[Dalymount Park]] on 7 March 1936 was attended by Brase leading the Army Band playing the Nazi national anthem, [[Deutschlandlied]], to which the attending Germans stood to attention with their right arms raised in a [[Nazi salute]] while singing.<ref>{{cite news |last=Croke |first=\nRuaidhr\u00ed |title=Ireland 5 Germany 2: When Nazi salutes took over Dalymount Park |work=Sport |publisher=[[Irish Times]] |date=29 October 2018 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/international/ireland-5-germany-2-when-nazi-salutes-took-over-dalymount-park-1.3678273 |accessdate=4 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nBrase was an active participant in the elaborate events, such as Christmas parties, held by the small German colony that took place in Dublin's grand hotels, the Royal Hibernian Hotel and [[Gresham Hotel]]s. At the 1937 event, Brase played piano to accompany the children's performance for the adults, as reported in both the [[Irish Independent]] and [[Irish Times]]. The latter report was likely written by its editor [[R. M. \"Bertie\" Smyllie|Robert Smylie]], a German speaker, was also an attendee.<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\"/>{{rp|63\u201365}}\n\n==Selected compositions==\n[[File:Fritz Brase's General Mulcahy March record label.jpg|thumb|''General Mulcahy March'' record label]]\n'''Brass band'''\n* ''Hoch die 7ten J\u00e4ger'' (1897)\n* ''Bienenhaus Marsch'' (c. 1900)\n* ''Jugenderinnerungen Marsch'' (1901)\n* ''Heil Danzig'' (1910)\n* ''Exzellenz von Bernhardi'' (1910)\n* ''Grosse Zeit, neue Zeit'' (1910)\n* ''General Mulcahy March'' (1923; Dublin: McCullough, 1924)\n* ''Irish March No. 2'' (1923; Dublin: McCullough, c. 1924)<ref>According to Ryan (1987, p. 61\u201362), this was written as \"No. 1\" but renumbered after the success of the ''General Mulcahy March'', which was then regarded as \"No. 1\").</ref>\n* ''Irish March No. 3'' (1923)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 1'' (1923; Dublin: McCullough [n. d.])\n* ''National March'' (1924)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 2'' (1924)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 3'' (1924)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 4'' (1925)<ref>Dedicated to [[Hamilton Harty]] (Ryan, 1987, p. 65\u201366).</ref>\n* ''Funeral March'' (1926)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 5'' (1927)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 6'' (1930)\n* ''Der Gott, der Eisen wachsen liess'' (1933)\n* ''Flieger-Escapaden'' (1935)\n\n'''Orchestra'''\n* ''Heimatlos'' (1902)\n* ''Dramatische Ouvert\u00fcre'' (1902)\n* Symphony in D major (1905)\n* ''Westfalen'' (1912)\n* ''Menuett'', for salon orchestra (1921, arrangement of piano work)\n* ''Paran\u00e1'', for salon orchestra (1926)\n* ''Irlandia'', suite (1932)\n* ''Episoden-Suite'' (1937)\n* ''Irish Dance No. 1: The Londonderry Clog'' (published 1938)\n* ''Irish Dance No. 2: The Frost is All Over'' (published 1938)\n* ''Irische Lustspiel-Ouvert\u00fcre'' (1939; Berlin: Musikverlag Sanssouci, 1959; reprint 1982)\n* ''Donegal''. Rhapsody for orchestra No. 2 (1939; reprint Berlin: Musikverlag Sanssouci, 1995)\n\n'''Piano'''\n* ''Strebe vorw\u00e4rts'', Op. 1\n* ''Mazurka brilliante'', Op. 2 (1894)\n* ''Mazurka brilliante'', Op. 4 (1895)\n* ''Waltz'', Op. 7 (1896)\n* ''Capriccio'', Op. 12 No. l (1898)\n* ''Die Garde an der Somme'' (c.1915\u201316)\n* ''Joska'' (1920)\n* ''Menuett'' (1921)\n* ''Pierette'' (1921)\n* ''Waldm\u00e4rchen'' (1921)\n* ''Orchideen'' (1922)\n* ''Herbst'' (1923)\n* ''Little Moira'', serenade (1925)\n* ''Horse Show March'' (1926)\n* ''Bi-centenary March 1731\u20131931'' (London: Boosey and Hawkes, 1931), [http://catalogue.nli.ie/Record/vtls000515940#page/2/mode/1up online]\n* ''Helden im Volksmund. Eine deutsche Rhapsodie'' (1933)\n\n'''Other'''\n* Several songs for voice and piano\n* Some chamber music, such as ''Nymphentanz'', Op. 9 (for violin and piano, 1898)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* John Brennock, \"The Army School of Music: The First Twenty Years\", in ''An cosant\u00f3ir'' vol. 13 no. 10 (October 1973), pp. 335\u2013341.\n* Joseph J. Ryan, ''The Army School of Music, 1922\u20131940: Its Formulation and Evolution with a Critical Assessment of its First Director, Wilhelm Fritz Brase'' (M.A. thesis, Maynooth University, 1987), [http://mural.maynoothuniversity.ie/5379/1/Joseph_Ryan_Vol-1_20140905081542.pdf volume 1], [http://mural.maynoothuniversity.ie/5379/2/Joseph_Ryan_Vol-2_20140905082825.pdf volume 2].\n* Gareth Cox and Joseph J. Ryan, \"Fritz Brase's Contribution to Irish Musical Life, 1923\u20131940\", in Joachim Fischer and Gisela Holfter (eds), ''Creative Influences: Selected Irish-German Biographies'' (Trier: Wissenschaftlicher Verlag, 2009), {{ISBN|978-3-86821-158-0}}, pp. 53\u201362.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 1'', performed by The Band of the Irish Guards, Andrew Chatburn (conductor), on: Specialist Recording Company SRC 121 (CD, 2003).\n* ''O'Donnell Ab\u00fa''; ''Irish Dance No. 2: The Frost is All Over''; ''Irish Army March (General Mulcahy March)''; John F. Larchet: ''Lament for Youth'' (arranged by Fritz Brase), performed by The Band of the Irish Defence Forces, Mark Armstrong (conductor), on: RT\u00c9 lyric fm CD 157 (CD, 2018).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brase, Fritz}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Jerome Cemetery and Crematorium]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish Army officers]]\n[[Category:Irish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Irish conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Irish male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Military musicians]]\n[[Category:Prussian Army personnel]]\n[[Category:University of Music and Theatre Leipzig alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German military bandmaster, conductor, and composer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Fritz Brase\n| image         = Colonel Fritz Brase.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Signed portrait of<br>Brase in Irish Army uniform\n| birth_name    = Friedrich Wilhelm Anton Brase\n| birth_date    = 4 May 1875\n| birth_place \u00a0 = [[Egestorf (Deister)|Egestorf]], Germany\n| death_date    = 1 December 1940 (age 65)\n| death_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Army band leader\n| years_active  = 1893\u20131940\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Friedrich Wilhelm Anton Brase''' (4 May 1875 \u2013 1 December 1940) was a German military [[bandmaster]], [[conductor]], and [[composer]] who was mainly active in Dublin, Ireland, as leader of the first [[Irish Defence Forces School of Music|Army School of Music]] in the [[Irish Free State]].\n\n==Life==\nBrase was the son of a miller born in [[Egestorf (Deister)|Egestorf]] near Hanover, Germany. Brase studied at the [[University of Music and Theatre Leipzig|Conservatory of Music at Leipzig]] where his teachers included [[Carl Reinecke]], [[Hans Sitt]], and [[Salomon Jadassohn]]. In 1923 he emigrated to Ireland,<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/> and a few years later he and his wife Elsa had a daughter, Mona, who was born while they lived at the [[Curragh Camp]].<ref name=\"RT\u00c9 doc\">{{cite AV media |people=Ryan, Captain Joseph (writer & presenter); Hughes, John (producer) |title=Wilhelm Maestro |medium=[https://podcast.rasset.ie/podcasts/2013/pc/pod-v-19038957m04swilhelmmaestrodoconone-pid0-3424608_audio.mp3 ''Documentary on One'' Podcast] |publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] |location=Dublin |date=1989 |url=https://www.rte.ie/radio1/doconone/2013/0612/647443-podcast-wilhelm-maestro-irish-army-school-of-music-band-no-1/ }}</ref> The family moved to accommodation in [[Beggars Bush Barracks]] and later bought their own house in the Dublin suburb of [[Sandymount]].<ref name=\"RT\u00c9 doc\"/>\n\nIn 1940, Brase died the day after he retired and was interred in [[Mount Jerome Cemetery and Crematorium|Mount Jerome Cemetery]], Dublin, when the No. 1 Irish Army Band played.<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\">{{Cite web |url=http://stores.militaryhistoryshop.com/blog/fritz-brase-irelands-prussian-bandmaster-/ |title=Fritz Brase: Ireland's Prussian Bandmaster |date=2016-01-20 |publisher=Brandenburg Historica |access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> His daughter Mona, who died on 2 November 2014, is also buried in Mount Jerome Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |title=BRASE, Mona: Death notice |work=Family Notices |publisher=[[Irish Times]] |date=5 November 2014 |url=https://notices.irishtimes.com/death/brase-mona/39512965 |accessdate=15 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\nA street in [[M\u00fcnster]] is named Braseweg in his memory.<ref>{{OpenStreetMap maps |url=https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=braseweg#map=18/51.97990/7.64548 |title=Braseweg, M\u00fcnster |accessdate=14 March 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"RT\u00c9 doc\"/>\n\n==Musical career==\nIn 1893, he enlisted in the military band at [[B\u00fcckeburg]] where his abilities as conductor and arranger qualified him for further studies at the [[Berlin University of the Arts|Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik, Berlin]], studying with [[Joseph Joachim]] and [[Max Bruch]].\nIn 1906, he was appointed conductor of the Infantry Regiment 13's band at M\u00fcnster and received early encouragement, when in 1909, at the age of 34, he was promoted [[Prussia|Prussian]] \"K\u00f6niglicher Musikdirektor\" (Royal Music Director).<ref>Joseph Ryan, \"Brase, [Wilhelm] Fritz [Anton]\", in ''The Enyclopaedia of Music in Ireland'' (Dublin: UCD Press, 2013), p. 124.</ref> In 1911, he was appointed conductor of the [[1st (Emperor Alexander) Guards Grenadiers]], \"one of the most prestigious positions in the world of German military music\".<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/> Following the German defeat in World War I, Brase was discharged from service in April 1919 and spent the following four years in various consignments including conducting a police band in Berlin.\n\nWhen Brase emigrated to Ireland in March 1923, he was attracted by the option of a rank as full colonel and  to take up the position of the first leader of the Army School of Music in the newly established Irish Free State.<ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/> Until 1928, he created four military bands in cooperation with a compatriot, Captain Friedrich Christian Sauerzweig, with Brase focusing on the \"Army No. 1 Band\". For independent Ireland, bringing over musicians from Germany was one way of breaking free from British influence.<ref>Joan FitzPatrick Dean, [https://books.google.de/books?id=8-jqBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA148&dq=Irish+Defence+Forces+School+of+Music&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Irish%20Defence%20Forces%20School%20of%20Music&f=false ''All Dressed Up. Modern Irish Historical Pageantry''] (Syracuse, NY: Syracuse University Press, 2014), pp. 147\u2013148.</ref> With his band, Brase toured Ireland extensively between the mid-1920s and early 1930s, playing at many festive occasions, both indoors and in public spaces. He also initialised a regular series of band concerts for primary schools in Dublin which, over the years, were attended by thousands of Irish school children.<ref>Ryan (2013).</ref> In 1927, he also co-founded the Dublin Philharmonic Society, a successful orchestra and chorus with a brass section recruited from the army band, which he directed until 1936 when he had to resign for health reasons. At the Army School of Music, he educated a number of prominent Irish musicians including [[Michael Bowles]], [[Arthur Duff]], and Dermot O'Hara.\n\n{{Quote box|width=300px|bgcolor=#E0E6F8|align=right|quote='''Recognition of Brase's contribution and achievements: [[Sir Anthony Esmonde, 15th Baronet|Anthony Charles Esmonde]] in [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] in November 1952'''<br>\n\n''When musical broadcasts were first organised in this country, under the late Colonel Fritz Brase, a German, he did not import a whole lot of foreign musicians. He recognised the fact that there was a fund of musical talent latent in the Irish people and he set out to develop that talent... but I think it is a pity that his policy was not continued, that this talent was not sought out and developed on a more extensive scale. That appears to me to be the difficulty with the orchestras in this country\u2014 that the talent that is there has not been sought out by the officials, the directors or whoever is in control of [[Radio \u00c9ireann]] and utilised so as to give employment to the fullest extent to Irish musicians and artistes.''<ref>{{cite web |title=D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann debate - Thursday, 6 Nov 1952 |work=D\u00e1il debates |publisher=[[Houses of the Oireachtas]] |date=6 November 1952 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1952-11-06/40/?highlight%5B0%5D=brase |accessdate=23 March 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Prussian Bandmaster\"/>}}\n\nBrase's influence on the cultural life of the nascent Irish republic was considerable and he was an ambitious composer who also wrote many works outside the military band repertory. He wrote a Symphony in D major that was performed in M\u00fcnster in 1908 and a number of other orchestral scores. For the army bands, he wrote many original scores (including the ''General Mulcahy March'' and six ''Irish Fantasias'') and arranged numerous Irish traditional tunes for military band. His first ''Irish Fantasia'' was played in 1926 at the opening broadcast of 2RN, the predecessor of today's [[Radio Telef\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]. He also wrote the station's official arrangement of the Irish national anthem.<ref>Ryan (2013).</ref>\n\n==German colony in Ireland==\nBrase was one of a small number of Germans and Austrians living in Ireland in the 1930s, several of whom had been brought there by the Irish Government, that included Brase and others, mostly involved in new industry the fledgling state was trying to develop. Otto Bene, leader of the [[Nazi Party]] in Britain and Ireland, living in London, visited Dublin to celebrate Hitler's birthday on 20 April 1933 in the presence of Brase and several others of the German colony that took place in the German Legation. Bene was responsible for recruiting Germans to the Nazi Party.<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\"/>{{rp|57, photo inter 128\u2013129}}\n\nEncouraged by Bene, the German colony set up a branch of the Nazi Party in 1934. Brase was its first elected chairman, however, when he requested permission from the [[Irish Army]] to lead the group, it was clearly suggested he choose between the two. He chose the army and his career<ref>David O'Donoghue, [https://www.historyireland.com/20th-century-contemporary-history/state-within-a-state-the-nazis-in-neutral-ireland/ \"State within a state: the Nazis in neutral Ireland\"], in ''History Ireland'', vol. 14 no. 6 (November/December 2006).</ref> allowing [[Adolf Mahr]], another German immigree and director of the [[National Museum of Ireland]], to assume the position.<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\">{{cite book |last=Mullins |first=Gerry |title=Dublin Nazi No. 1: The Life of Adolf Mahr |publisher=[[Liberties Press]] |date=2007 |location=Dublin |pages= |isbn=978-1-905483-20-4 }}</ref>{{rp|56\u201357}} Bene again came to Dublin in 1935 to attend Brase' 60th birthday party in the family home in [[Sandymount]].<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\nThe soccer match between Germany and Ireland, that Ireland won 5 to 2, at [[Dalymount Park]] on 7 March 1936 was attended by Brase leading the Army Band playing the Nazi national anthem, [[Deutschlandlied]], to which the attending Germans stood to attention with their right arms raised in a [[Nazi salute]] while singing.<ref>{{cite news |last=Croke |first=\nRuaidhr\u00ed |title=Ireland 5 Germany 2: When Nazi salutes took over Dalymount Park |work=Sport |publisher=[[Irish Times]] |date=29 October 2018 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/international/ireland-5-germany-2-when-nazi-salutes-took-over-dalymount-park-1.3678273 |accessdate=4 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nBrase was an active participant in the elaborate events, such as Christmas parties, held by the small German colony that took place in Dublin's grand hotels, the Royal Hibernian Hotel and [[Gresham Hotel]]s. At the 1937 event, Brase played piano to accompany the children's performance for the adults, as reported in both the [[Irish Independent]] and [[Irish Times]]. The latter report was likely written by its editor [[R. M. \"Bertie\" Smyllie|Robert Smylie]], a German speaker, was also an attendee.<ref name=\"Adolf Mahr\"/>{{rp|63\u201365}}\n\n==Selected compositions==\n[[File:Fritz Brase's General Mulcahy March record label.jpg|thumb|''General Mulcahy March'' record label]]\n'''Brass band'''\n* ''Hoch die 7ten J\u00e4ger'' (1897)\n* ''Bienenhaus Marsch'' (c. 1900)\n* ''Jugenderinnerungen Marsch'' (1901)\n* ''Heil Danzig'' (1910)\n* ''Exzellenz von Bernhardi'' (1910)\n* ''Grosse Zeit, neue Zeit'' (1910)\n* ''General Mulcahy March'' (1923; Dublin: McCullough, 1924)\n* ''Irish March No. 2'' (1923; Dublin: McCullough, c. 1924)<ref>According to Ryan (1987, p. 61\u201362), this was written as \"No. 1\" but renumbered after the success of the ''General Mulcahy March'', which was then regarded as \"No. 1\").</ref>\n* ''Irish March No. 3'' (1923)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 1'' (1923; Dublin: McCullough [n. d.])\n* ''National March'' (1924)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 2'' (1924)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 3'' (1924)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 4'' (1925)<ref>Dedicated to [[Hamilton Harty]] (Ryan, 1987, p. 65\u201366).</ref>\n* ''Funeral March'' (1926)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 5'' (1927)\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 6'' (1930)\n* ''Der Gott, der Eisen wachsen liess'' (1933)\n* ''Flieger-Escapaden'' (1935)\n\n'''Orchestra'''\n* ''Heimatlos'' (1902)\n* ''Dramatische Ouvert\u00fcre'' (1902)\n* Symphony in D major (1905)\n* ''Westfalen'' (1912)\n* ''Menuett'', for salon orchestra (1921, arrangement of piano work)\n* ''Paran\u00e1'', for salon orchestra (1926)\n* ''Irlandia'', suite (1932)\n* ''Episoden-Suite'' (1937)\n* ''Irish Dance No. 1: The Londonderry Clog'' (published 1938)\n* ''Irish Dance No. 2: The Frost is All Over'' (published 1938)\n* ''Irische Lustspiel-Ouvert\u00fcre'' (1939; Berlin: Musikverlag Sanssouci, 1959; reprint 1982)\n* ''Donegal''. Rhapsody for orchestra No. 2 (1939; reprint Berlin: Musikverlag Sanssouci, 1995)\n\n'''Piano'''\n* ''Strebe vorw\u00e4rts'', Op. 1\n* ''Mazurka brilliante'', Op. 2 (1894)\n* ''Mazurka brilliante'', Op. 4 (1895)\n* ''Waltz'', Op. 7 (1896)\n* ''Capriccio'', Op. 12 No. l (1898)\n* ''Die Garde an der Somme'' (c.1915\u201316)\n* ''Joska'' (1920)\n* ''Menuett'' (1921)\n* ''Pierette'' (1921)\n* ''Waldm\u00e4rchen'' (1921)\n* ''Orchideen'' (1922)\n* ''Herbst'' (1923)\n* ''Little Moira'', serenade (1925)\n* ''Horse Show March'' (1926)\n* ''Bi-centenary March 1731\u20131931'' (London: Boosey and Hawkes, 1931), [http://catalogue.nli.ie/Record/vtls000515940#page/2/mode/1up online]\n* ''Helden im Volksmund. Eine deutsche Rhapsodie'' (1933)\n\n'''Other'''\n* Several songs for voice and piano\n* Some chamber music, such as ''Nymphentanz'', Op. 9 (for violin and piano, 1898)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* John Brennock, \"The Army School of Music: The First Twenty Years\", in ''An cosant\u00f3ir'' vol. 13 no. 10 (October 1973), pp. 335\u2013341.\n* Joseph J. Ryan, ''The Army School of Music, 1922\u20131940: Its Formulation and Evolution with a Critical Assessment of its First Director, Wilhelm Fritz Brase'' (M.A. thesis, Maynooth University, 1987), [http://mural.maynoothuniversity.ie/5379/1/Joseph_Ryan_Vol-1_20140905081542.pdf volume 1], [http://mural.maynoothuniversity.ie/5379/2/Joseph_Ryan_Vol-2_20140905082825.pdf volume 2].\n* Gareth Cox and Joseph J. Ryan, \"Fritz Brase's Contribution to Irish Musical Life, 1923\u20131940\", in Joachim Fischer and Gisela Holfter (eds), ''Creative Influences: Selected Irish-German Biographies'' (Trier: Wissenschaftlicher Verlag, 2009), {{ISBN|978-3-86821-158-0}}, pp. 53\u201362.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''Irish Fantasia No. 1'', performed by The Band of the Irish Guards, Andrew Chatburn (conductor), on: Specialist Recording Company SRC 121 (CD, 2003).\n* ''O'Donnell Ab\u00fa''; ''Irish Dance No. 2: The Frost is All Over''; ''Irish Army March (General Mulcahy March)''; John F. Larchet: ''Lament for Youth'' (arranged by Fritz Brase), performed by The Band of the Irish Defence Forces, Mark Armstrong (conductor), on: RT\u00c9 lyric fm CD 157 (CD, 2018).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brase, Fritz}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Jerome Cemetery and Crematorium]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish Army officers]]\n[[Category:Irish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Irish conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Irish male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Military musicians]]\n[[Category:Prussian Army personnel]]\n[[Category:University of Music and Theatre Leipzig alumni]]\n", "name_user": "LittleWink", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toConductor(link changed toConducting) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fritz_Brase"}
{"title_page": "John Golden (pirate)", "text_new": "{{for|the American actor|John Golden}}\n{{other people|John Golding}}\n\n'''John Golden'''{{efn|Last name occasionally spelled Golden, Ooldin, or Golding. He was tried alongside fellow crewman John Gold, with whom he should not be confused.}} (died 1694) was a [[Jacobitism|Jacobite]] pirate and [[privateer]] active in the waters near [[England]] and [[France]]. His trial was important in establishing [[Admiralty law]], differentiating between privateers and pirates, and ending the naval ambitions of the deposed [[James II of England|James II]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n[[James II of England|Catholic King James II]] was deposed in late 1688 in favor of Protestant rulers [[William III of England|William]] and [[Mary II of England|Mary]]. Retreating to France, he issued privateering commissions in concert with France's [[King Louis XIV]] to aid in harassing English forces at sea. Golden used one such commission with his ship ''Sun Privateer'' to capture the English frigate ''James Galley'' in late 1692.<ref name=\"An account of the tryals\" /> En route to France they were recaptured by the English vessel ''Prince of Orange'', then returned to England and imprisoned at [[Marshalsea Prison|Marshalsea]] to await trial.<ref name=\"An account of the tryals\" />\n\nGolden argued that his French privateering commission via James II was still valid, and that as such he should be treated as a [[prisoner of war]] and not tried as a pirate.<ref name=\"Boon\">{{cite book|last1=Boon|first1=Kristen|title=Piracy and International Maritime Security|date=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=9780199758210|pages=67\u201368|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PeZMAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> He and his crew also quoted the [[Treaty of Limerick]], which allowed English subjects to serve foreign rulers militarily.<ref name=\"Kay - The Glorious Revolution\">{{cite book|last1=Kay|first1=Richard S.|title=The Glorious Revolution and the Continuity of Law|date=2014|publisher=CUA Press|location=Washington DC|isbn=9780813226873|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ODkjBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> The King's [[Admiralty Advocate]] William Oldys{{efn|Also Oldiss or Oldish; he was the father of bibliographer and antiquarian [[William Oldys]].}} agreed and refused to prosecute them for piracy.<ref name=\"Durston - The Admiralty Sessions\" /> Other officials disagreed and removed Oldys, replacing him with Fisher Littleton, who agreed to prosecute some of the prisoners as pirates but tried Golden and a few supporters for treason instead. [[Matthew Tindall]], who later wrote about the case, supported Littleton's position.<ref name=\"Neo - The Universal Adversary\">{{cite book|last1=Neocleous|first1=Mark|title=The Universal Adversary: Security, Capital and 'The Enemies of All Mankind'|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=9781317355434|pages=116\u2013117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-YGPCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> Littleton argued that a deposed ruler had no authority to commission privateers and therefore Golden and his crew had no protections under law.<ref name=\"Durston - The Admiralty Sessions\" /> The Treaty of Limerick forbade English subjects from serving against England and the Court rejected it as a defense.<ref name=\"Kay - The Glorious Revolution\" />\n\nConvicted of treason for making war against William and Mary in the name of a foreign ruler, Golden and two others appealed to the court, arguing that being deposed did not deprive James II of his authority as King and laid out several arguments supporting their claim to be treated as prisoners of war.<ref name=\"Kay - The Glorious Revolution\" /> The Court rejected their Jacobite arguments: \u201cthrough Ignorance, as supposing the Commission he acted under sufficient to warrant his Illegal Proceedings; the Jury being directed by the Court as to matter of Fact, he was found Guilty of High-Treason.\u201d<ref name=\"An account of the tryals\">{{cite book|last1=Clare|first1=J|title=An account of the tryals of Captain J. Golden. Thomas Jones. John Gold. Lawrance Maliene. Patrick Whitley. John Slaughter. Const. D'Heaity. Richard Shewers. Darby Collins. John Ryon. Dennis Cockram. John Walsh. At the Court of Admiralty held in the Marshalsea in Southwark, before the Right Honourable the Judges: on monday the 25th. of Feb. 1693/4. Of which 9 were found guilty, and received sentence of death: 3 for high treason, and 6 for piracies and roberys on the seas, under the colour of the late King James's commission. Licens'd Feb. 27th. 1693/4|date=1694|publisher=The Globe|location=London|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo2/A26179.0001.001?rgn=main;view=fulltext|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref> In March 1694 they were hanged, drawn, and quartered. Six others were convicted of piracy and were hanged, while a further four{{efn|Two of the men accused of piracy were named Richard Shivers and Dennis Cockram, who should not be confused with unrelated pirates [[Dirk Chivers|Richard (Dirk) Chivers]] or [[John Cockram|John (Thomas) Cockram]].}} were acquitted and released.  Within two years James II ceased offering privateering commissions.<ref name=\"Durston - The Admiralty Sessions\">{{cite book|last1=Durston|first1=Gregory|title=The Admiralty Sessions, 1536-1834: Maritime Crime and the Silver Oar|date=2017|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|location=Newcastle upon Tyne|isbn=9781443873611|pages=164\u2013165|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jVwpDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover|accessdate=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jean Baptiste Guedry]] \u2013 An [[Acadia]]n whose trial for piracy was used to teach locals as an example of English Admiralty law.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=BFZTAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=golding&f=false Proceedings before the Lords of the Council and the Admiralty] and [https://books.google.com/books?id=f7d5SpAFk6wC&printsec=frontcover#v=snippet&q=golding&f=false Proceedings of the Privy Council against Doctor Oldys], for the full text of Oldys' reasoning in refusing to prosecute Golden and his crew, Tindall's comments, Golden's petition to the Court, and Littleton's response to Oldys\n\n{{pirates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden, John}}\n[[Category:17th-century pirates]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:English privateers]]\n[[Category:English pirates]]\n[[Category:People executed for piracy]]\n[[Category:1694 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American actor|John Golden}}\n{{for2|other people named John Golding|[[John Golding (disambiguation)|John Golding]]}}\n\n'''John Golden'''{{efn|Last name occasionally spelled Golden, Ooldin, or Golding. He was tried alongside fellow crewman John Gold, with whom he should not be confused.}} (died 1694) was a [[Jacobitism|Jacobite]] pirate and [[privateer]] active in the waters near [[England]] and [[France]]. His trial was important in establishing [[Admiralty law]], differentiating between privateers and pirates, and ending the naval ambitions of the deposed [[James II of England|James II]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n[[James II of England|Catholic King James II]] was deposed in late 1688 in favor of Protestant rulers [[William III of England|William]] and [[Mary II of England|Mary]]. Retreating to France, he issued privateering commissions in concert with France's [[King Louis XIV]] to aid in harassing English forces at sea. Golden used one such commission with his ship ''Sun Privateer'' to capture the English frigate ''James Galley'' in late 1692.<ref name=\"An account of the tryals\" /> En route to France they were recaptured by the English vessel ''Prince of Orange'', then returned to England and imprisoned at [[Marshalsea Prison|Marshalsea]] to await trial.<ref name=\"An account of the tryals\" />\n\nGolden argued that his French privateering commission via James II was still valid, and that as such he should be treated as a [[prisoner of war]] and not tried as a pirate.<ref name=\"Boon\">{{cite book|last1=Boon|first1=Kristen|title=Piracy and International Maritime Security|date=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=9780199758210|pages=67\u201368|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PeZMAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> He and his crew also quoted the [[Treaty of Limerick]], which allowed English subjects to serve foreign rulers militarily.<ref name=\"Kay - The Glorious Revolution\">{{cite book|last1=Kay|first1=Richard S.|title=The Glorious Revolution and the Continuity of Law|date=2014|publisher=CUA Press|location=Washington DC|isbn=9780813226873|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ODkjBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> The King's [[Admiralty Advocate]] William Oldys{{efn|Also Oldiss or Oldish; he was the father of bibliographer and antiquarian [[William Oldys]].}} agreed and refused to prosecute them for piracy.<ref name=\"Durston - The Admiralty Sessions\" /> Other officials disagreed and removed Oldys, replacing him with Fisher Littleton, who agreed to prosecute some of the prisoners as pirates but tried Golden and a few supporters for treason instead. [[Matthew Tindall]], who later wrote about the case, supported Littleton's position.<ref name=\"Neo - The Universal Adversary\">{{cite book|last1=Neocleous|first1=Mark|title=The Universal Adversary: Security, Capital and 'The Enemies of All Mankind'|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=9781317355434|pages=116\u2013117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-YGPCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&